<LP>
   TIMOTHY RYAN WON Senate approval to be the nation's top
savings and loan regulator, effectively nullifying a court
decision that had derailed the overhaul of the S&amp;L industry.
The surprisingly wide margin of 62-37 in favor of Ryan
followed a six-hour debate about whether the labor lawyer is
qualified for the job.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   UAL's board meets today to consider a sweetened buy-out
bid from United Air's unions valued at over $200 a share, or
$4.36 billion. Though several directors appeared to favor the
new bid, it faces strong opposition from UAL's chairman,
Stephen Wolf.
   ---
   Circle K reached a preliminary accord with senior
creditors and its largest shareholder to delay debt payments
for seven months, narrowly averting a partial default.
   ---
   Ford agreed to pay $6 million to settle a personal-injury
suit involving lap-only seat belts in the rear seats of its
Escort model. The huge settlement likely will add impetus to
the debate over the safety of such belts.
   ---
   Treasury bonds rallied and stocks fell on rumors that a
big institutional investor in the Tokyo stock market was in
financial trouble. The Dow Jones industrials closed off
17.34, at 2719.37. The dollar finished mixed.
                                                                                                       

   The Group of Seven industrial nations gather in Paris this
Saturday to try to shore up the yen and improve the
coordination of economic policy.
   ---
   Baxter International will take a $566 million
first-quarter charge to cover plant closings, a 10% cut in
its work force, and the elimination of certain lines. The
charge will nearly wipe out the health-care products and
services firm's profit for the year.
   ---
   U.S. car and truck sales rose 2.9% in late March, helped
by hefty cash rebates and some unusual incentives. The gain
sparked optimism among auto makers despite continued
uncertainty about the economy and rates.
   ---
   Tax-increase options being prepared for the House Budget
panel's chairman include raising the top corporate rate and
limiting the deduction for state and local taxes.
   ---
   Stock mutual funds generally beat the market for the first
time in two years, though they still were down an average
2.31% for the first quarter.
   ---
   Bank of New England plans to cut its work force by 5,600
employees, or about one-third, as expected. But the bank
acknowledged it faces further increases in nonperforming
assets and loan-loss provisions.
   ---
   Most of Bonwit Teller's retail stores were ordered
liquidated by a bankruptcy court, which rejected lastminute
appeals to save the chain.
   ---
   News Corp.'s Fox Film unit is joining the growing wave of
Hollywood studios and production firms seeking Japanese
financial backing.
   ---
   The alcoholic-beverage industry is in a rage over a bill
introduced in Congress yesterday that would require health
warnings in all ads.
   ---
   A big Avon shareholder, Chartwell Associates, boosted its
stake to over 15% from 10%, sources said. Avon's stock
climbed $1.25, to $35.25.
   ---
   Tougher job-discrimination rules were approved by the
Senate Labor panel. The bill is aimed at countering recent
Supreme Court decisions that made job bias harder to prove.
   ---
